column168: Our vehicle, a tractor pulling a 10,000 gal tank trailer of liquid propane, was traveling north on Interstate 93, onto Laconia Rd, he did so in the right lane of travel. As he made this left corner, his speed was unsafe and the TT unit he was operating with the attached trailer and load, overturned, coming to rest on the embankment between the roadway and a local restaurant, Tilt'n Diner. The propane tank was emptied prior to removal. The area businesses and roadways were shut down and evacuated as a precaution against explosion. There was absolutely NO leakage of any amount.
column169: Additional training for drivers in regards to cornering with full loads. This driver was actually terminated after the incident.

column168: On 2 November 2017, about 1718 hours, an undeclared UN1263 gallon of Paint leaked from a USPS mail parcel.  USPS Tracking number: CX 564 410 347 CA.  Description of Contents "Old Car Parts", shipper did not declare the paint. Paint leaked from parcel in aircraft compartment.  Shipment originated in Canada, tendered by USPS in Chicago, IL, and first flight was from ORD to DFW.  During transit, it is assumed pressure caused paint can lid to open and caused the spill.    Outer packaging was not adequate for this HAZMAT.    Aircraft was removed from service, cleaned, and put back into service after thorough inspection.

column168: While conducting an inspection of the waste storage area, a Safety-Kleen employee notice a small amount of liquid on the floor. The employee inspected the drums in the immediate area and a small amount of liquid was noticed on the side of one drum.  After inspecting the drum to determine if any pressure was present the employee removed the lid and found approximately a 3" section of lid gasket missing.  The lid gasket was replaced and the spill area was cleaned up.  The cleanup material placed into an appropriate drum and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: Notified the customer and reminded them to inspect the lid gaskets before the closing the drum.

column168: During routine inspection at the 10 day storage facility, a small amount of liquid was found to be leaking from a staged roll-off container. Soil was impacted; no waterways near. In proper personnel protective equipment, the driver was able to remediate the area. Absorbent material was added to the roll-off box to further solidify the small amount of liquid in the waste stream. The roll-off box was transported and disposed of without further incident. A courtesy report was made to Utah Department of Environmental Quality, to John Perry, who elected not to input into the State system.

column168: Event # 66858..    Driver began to unload and product leaked out of the fitting to the external valve.. Driver changed the gasket and tightened up the external valve and the leak stopped..    Release lasted less than 5 minutes and that approximately three (3) quarts were released.. The consignee employee put something on it that turned it to "powder" form and then they were able to hose it off..

The driver was attempting to hook up his hose to a connection that was difficult due to the fact the environmental bucket was slightly tilted up. The bucket was angled up due to the fact that when it was installed, it was pushed up under the dirt and rocks. To add to the issues the driver was using a made up 4 inch to 3 inch swedged connection that caused it to be very close to the lip of the bucket. When the driver tried to make his connection, he did not get the hose seated into the connection well enough so that when he opened up the tank valve, it separated causing the spill.    Driver shut off valve as soon as it leaked and stopped the flow.  He notified management and site ownership who assisted in the cleanup.
column169: Incident was investigated and environmental box was dugout deeper so more room was given.  All drivers were trained on what to look for to ensure a firm connection before starting flow.  If firm connection cannot be obtained, do not start flow of product.

NRC was mobilized to inspect and secure/remediate impacted soil and found top operated bottom outlet valve to be 1/4 turn open.
column169: Inspect all valves and secondary closures to ensure tank car is secure for transportation prior to offering.

column168: One (55) gallon drum of PYRIDINE (Hazardous) was discovered as the source of the leak. Less than one gallon leaked from the drum onto the  container deck. The compromised drum was located at the rear stack, against the right sidewall. It was compromised at the bottom portion due to the  drum rubbing against the D Ring located at the container sidewall. United Pumping overpacked the compromised drum for transport to their facility. All  remaining cargo was properly loaded back into the container and secured for safe intermodal transit.
column169: Ensure drums loaded for transport are properly blocked and braced to prevent abrasion during transport.

column168: On 11/12/2017 at 1800 hours CST, I was advised of a tank car leaking at the Indiana Harbor Belt (IHB) Rail yard in Riverdale, IL. IHB Transportation advised car number MTZX 330369 appeared to be leaking vapors from the protective housing. It was first reported as a strong odor of natural gas by the IHB Car Dept. The tank car was a load of UN3295 Hydrocarbons, Liquid N.O.S. Hazard Class 3 flammable liquid, packing group 1. Tracks BSY9, 8, 7 were all shut down the the Blue Island South Yard.     Upon arrival myself and hazmat contractor Response Management Services (RMS) inspected the car and found that the liquid valve in the protective housing was not fully shut. There was audible and visual evidence of the leak. You could hear the pressure coming out of the plug and also see bubbling on the threads of the plug. There was also a small amount of product dripping out of the plug. After tightening the valve with a wrench and removing the plug and cleaning it and applying new tape the leak was stopped. It is unclear how much product was lost in transportation to the IHB. The car came from Aux Sable Liquid Products in Morris, IL and was headed to Savage Services in Hammond, IN.

column168: LARRY RUSH DISCOVERED THE PACKAGE ON PD 10. HE DID NOT KNOW THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING. HE WENT TO TAKE IT TO PD 7 CLERK STATION AND WHEN HE SET IT DOWN HE DISCOVERED IT WAS LEAKING AND HAD IT ON HIS HANDS. HE TOLD HIS SUPERVISOR THAT HIS HAND WAS BURNING. MIKE HALL, HIS SUPERVISOR, PROCEEDED TO BRING LARRY AND THE HAZ MAT TO THE DMP CAGE. WE LOOKED UP THE MSDS AND TO IDENTIFY THE CORRECT RESPONSE FOR THE EMPLOYEE REGARDING SKIN CONTACT. THE MSDS SUGGESTED TO WASH HANDS WITH COLD WATER. LARRY DID THIS AND FELT RELIEF AND WAS ABLE TO RETURN TO WORK. WE, THE RESPONDERS, FOLLOWED THE RESPONSE ACTION SHEET TO NEUTRALIZE AND SOLIDIFY THE SPILL. WE THEN PROCEEDED TO PROCESS THE PACKAGE THROUGH DMP.
column169: EMPLOYEES SHOULD VISUALLY INSPECT EACH PACKAGE TO ENSURE THE CONTENTS ARE NOT LEAKING BEFORE PICKING UP THE PACKAGE.

column162: SVP HEALTH SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: While offloading a trailer, facility personnel noticed a release from a container staged on a pallet. Facility personnel, in proper personal protective equipment, were able to offload the container and stage it into a secondary containment. The trailer floor was impacted; no soil or waterways were impacted by the release. An internal response team, in personal protective equipment, was dispatched to repack the container and its contents, as well as to decontaminate the trailer. Remediation efforts were satisfactory and the waste was sent to its final disposal destination without further incident. Texas Commission on Environmental Quality was notified and state report 2017-3656 was generated.
column169: Facility management contacted the generator and informed them of the release. Generator was advised on proper container selection prior to offering waste into transportation. Generator has elected to begin utilizing a different container for this waste stream. Driver was retrained on thorough container inspection, prior to acceptance into transportation.

column168: On November 05, 2017 the driver for the DOT406 Tanker was making a delivery and was filling an under ground storage tank with UN1203 Unleaded Gasoline at a gas station. The storage tank over filled causing approximately 50-gallons of the gasoline to release to the asphalt parking lot and soil shoulder. No water ways or drains were reported to have been impacted. column168: An employee was off loading drums off of a Veolia vehicle at the Veolia in-transit facility located in Schenectady, NY when he noticed liquid leaking from a 5 gal open-top poly drum. The estimated spill release was 2 gallons onto the floor of the Veolia vehicle and an estimated 200 ml that leaked from the truck onto the paved ground at the the Veolia In-Transit Facility. The 5 gal open-top poly drum (bucket) had tape around the cover suggesting the cover was not secure causing the release. The employee used absorbent and spill pads to clean up the spill release. To prevent any further release the employee over-packed the 5 gal poly drum into a 14 gal fiber drum with absorbent. The employee reported the spill to the local Veolia EHS department.
column169: The Veolia employee was retrained on the drum inspection process that must be conducted before accepting shipments from Veolia customers. Inspection improvements have been made and are being performed by the Veolia employee.

column168: Tank car UTLX 952001 was found emanating vapors in the BNSF Railyard at Mandan, ND on 11/25/2017.  The BNSF Responder reported leak source was at UTLX 952001 protective housing.  After inspection it was verified the vapor valve was not properly closed and the secondary closure plug was not tool tight.  BNSF Railway responder closed the vapor valve and properly tool tightened the secondary closure plug, which mitigated the release.    MULTIPLE #1  Tank car SRIX 33977 was reported emanating vapors in the BNSF Railyard at Mandan, ND on 11/25/2017.  The BNSF responder reported leak source was at SRIX 33977 protective housing.  After inspection it was verified that the liquid valve was open and the secondary closure plug was less than tool tight.  BNSF Railway responder properly closed the liquid valve and tool tightened the secondary closure plug.
column169: Ensure the shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: At approximately 08:00 on November 2, 2017, a quad axel truck spilled approximately 1000 to 1500 pounds of RCRA hazardous waste solids on the exit pad of the facility’s scale.     Facility personnel responded to the spill by building a gravel berm around the affected area. The spilled material was recovered. An affected area of gravel service road exiting the scale was excavated to an approximate depth of six (6) inches. The recovered material and excavated gravel were transported to the active working face of the landfill, off loaded, and buried following the facility’s receiving and unloading procedures.  The concrete was pressure washed and the liquids recovered; approximately 85-gallons. The recovered liquid was placed in the facility’s leachate collection tank which is managed as a 90-day generator tank for F039 leachate.
column169: The incident investigation determined the cause as human error by the driver. The driver failed to fully tighten the tailgate turnbuckles.  The truck crossed the speedbump exiting the facility’s scale causing the tailgate to jar open.  The employee received a written reprimand with document consequences of any future failure to follow established operating procedures.

column168: On November 24, 2017 at 1840 ET, a Crossett CTMV was off-loading diesel fuel at a customer location when the transfer line allowed for a release due to a mechanical failure which the hose line and hose line coupling. The release was immediate and stopped once the operator stopped the transfer. Approximately 25 gallons released to a 100' x 6' area of the asphalt parking lot. No drains or waterways were impacted. A contractor was dispatched for cleanup. All cleanup debris was containerized and taken off site for proper disposal.

column168: At approximately 1030 am on Monday, 11/27/17, the subject truck was travelling Eastbound on I-40 in Winston-Salem, NC and the driver was flagged down by another driver to let him know there was a leak coming from his fuel tank. He parked so that the tank would leak on the pavement so that none would be released to the soil.    The driver called his dispatcher and 911.  The dispatcher contacted the Operations Manager who called a cleanup crew to be dispatched to this location.      Upon arrival and calculating fuel amounts, it was determined that 23 gallons was spilled to the pavement.

column168: Screener x-rayed both cardboard boxes of shipment and noticed aerosol cans.  She opened the box and found one 12 oz. aerosol can of NAPA Pro Cleen, and ten 4 fl. oz. plastic bottles of Ethanol Shield fuel stabilizer.  According to the SDS for Ethanol Shield, it may not be hazmat due to the high flash point, but the FAA inspector will make that determination.  FAA inspector cleared shipment on Friday, Dec 01 but there is no indication as to whether the Ethanol Shield was cleared.  Will file report for those items once I hear back from lead on duty.  All 11 pieces of possible undeclared hazmat were removed from the box, pictures taken and the entire shipment put on hold.  A report was filed through our carrier's report system, then the 5800.1 started.  I am completing it now for the Pro Cleen.
column169: Each point of contact with customer, reiterate undeclared hazmat rules.  Shippers such as NAPA, or contents stating auto parts would be something to pay closer attention to as the possibility for undeclared hazmat is higher than other shipments.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED, PALED AND SPLIT TO THE DOGHOUSE. THE PACKAGE WAS CAUGHT IN A JAM. THE PACKAGE COMPRESSED JUST ENOUGH FOR THE PACKAGE TO DISCHARGE 3 OZ. OF PRODUCT. column168: On 11/19/17 at approximately 08:05 PST, the ECLX 16062 was found to have a small leak of Potassium Hydroxide solution from the bottom outlet valve nozzle.  BNSF Hazmat member inspected the car and found the top operated bottom outlet valve to be partially open (1/4 turn) contributing to the release.  The valve was closed and the leak subsided.  While inspecting the BOV nozzle, the shipper had a 3"-2" bushing, a nipple and a 2" valve with a plug.  The leak through the open TOBOV was leaking past the threads on the 2" nipple above the valve.  Responders drained the remaining liquid in the nozzle, removed the 2" nipple (with valve assembly) which was cross-threaded/mis-alinged and installed the 2" plug in the bushing to seal the bottom of the car.  The removed parts were secured in the valve housing for the shipper/consignee to use for closer inspection.  The potassium hydroxide that had leaked from the car and impacted the nozzle was neutralized and cleaned.
column169: Shipper should ensure that all fittings and components on the tank car are secured prior to offering for transportation.  This includes inspection and closing of the TOBOV valve and securement of the packing nut.  Additionally, secondary closures should be inspected for signs of leakage or alignment affecting the seal of the component.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste at the intermediate truck transfer facility was being unloaded for consolidation into a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility. The forklift operator misjudged his clearance and punctured a drum with the forklift blade. The waste release impacted only the trailer floor; no soil, asphalt, or water was affected. A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and over-packed the drum into a suitable salvage drum. As directed by the local fire department, the rest of the trailer contents were unloaded so that the trailer floor could be thoroughly cleaned. The absorbent material used to clean up the trailer floor was placed into the over pack. Additional absorbents generated during the cleanup were placed into a suitable drum, and disposed of in the appropriate waste stream. The over-pack continued to its final destination without further incident.
column169: The forklift operator was advised to use better care and caution when loading and unloading drums. He was not allowed to operate a forklift until he completed forklift operation retraining.

column168: On November 14, 2017 at 16:50 hours, personnel in the CSXT Radnor yard reported product leaking from the top of QOTX 285, a loaded tank car of Furaldehydes.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Odfjell Terminals, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2017-1114-00200.  Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that 4 of the 6 manway cover swing bolts were less than tool tight.  Additionally, MEI found that the secondary securement plug on the sample line valve was not installed.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative Cheryl Kennedy (713-844-2312).  Contractor personnel opened the manway, inspected the manway gasket, and properly secured all manway cover bolts. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.    NARRI: 5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100  Cause Code: 212
column169: (NARRI: 212)

column168: During routine inspection, facility personnel found a release from a container staged on a pallet in the 10 day permitted storage area. In appropriate personal protective equipment, personnel successfully remediated the impacted area; concrete only, no soil, storm drains or water ways in the vicinity. The compromised container was over-packed and the waste stream was sent to its final destination without further incident.
column169: Facility personnel were re-trained on thorough container inspection. Generator was notified of release and advised of selecting compliant containers prior to offering waste into transportation.

column162: SVP HEALTH SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: During the offloading process of a van trailer, facility personnel at the 10 day storage facility found contamination on the outside of a non-bulk container. Upon investigation, it was determined the drum was not closed fully to manufactures specifications. The release only contaminated the container; no concrete, soil, water ways or storm drains were impacted. In appropriate personal protective equipment, personnel successfully overpacked the container into a proper UN spec rated salvage drum. The container was sent to its final destination without further incident. No state reporting was required for this release, as it was below the reportable quantity for this material for the state of Texas.
column169: The driver was re-trained on container inspection and non-bulk closure, with an emphasis of thoroughly inspecting containers prior to acceptance into transportation and understanding the manufacturer’s specifications on container closure, including proper torqueing and bolt/nut placement.

column168: On November 14, 2017 a driver for Landstar noticed that a (1) 330-gallon poly tote containing UN3266 Heavy Duty Liquid Alkaline Cleaner "Liquid BR5512-LAB" had become punctured by other freight during a load shift. Approximately 40-gallons released to the trailer floor and underlying asphalt parking lot. No waterways, soils, or drains were reported to have been impacted. A contractor was dispatched who contained, neutralized, and cleaned the release by utilizing granular absorbents and soda ash. A tote transfer was conducted for the remaining salvaged material. The contractor took all generated waste offsite for proper disposal.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was parked awaiting shipment to a intended waste disposal facility when, during a routine inspection, facility personnel noticed that there was release from the trailer to the asphalt parking lot. Only the trailer and asphalt were impacted; no soil or water were affected. Spill buckets and absorbents were immediately deployed. A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer, and found a single drum had developed a small pin hole leak near the bottom chime. The drum was over-packed into a suitable UN rated container, and the waste continued to its final destination without incident. The trailer and asphalt were neutralized and cleaned, and the waste generated from the cleanup was drummed and placed in the appropriate facility waste stream.    There was evidence that this hole was the result of internal corrosion, and that the waste material was incompatible with the steel drum.      This release did not meet the minimum reporting guidelines for the State of Ohio.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. This release was the direct result of improper container selection and preparation. The shipper was notified and advised to use an appropriate UN rated container for future shipments of this waste stream.

A SEMI-TRUCK TRANSMISSION ON A PALLET WAS LOADED ON TOP OF THE TOTE. THE HEAVY WEIGHT OF THE TRANSMISSION PUNCTURED THE TOTE AND CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE TO BE RELEASED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. ONCE THE RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED THE LOCATION PUT DOWN ABSORBENT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, AND ABSORBENT PADS ON THE TOP OF THE TOTE TO HELP PREVENT ANY FURTHER RELEASE.     HAZ-MAT RESPONSE WAS CALLED TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP OF THE TRAILER FLOOR AND TO TRANSFER THE CONTENTS OF THE TOTE INTO A REPLACEMENT TOTE.
column169: DISCUSS AND RETRAIN PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES WITH TERMINALS AND DRIVERS. HAVE THE DRIVERS INSPECT THE TRAILER TO ENSURE THE FREIGHT HAS BEEN PROPERLY LOADED, AND IF IT HAS NOT TO CORRECTLY LOAD IT PRIOR TO DEPARTING

column168: The carrier driver left the shipper and while at a stop light was told that hazmat was leaking from the CTMV.  Upon inspection, driver discovered the rear 3" wash out was missing its cover.  Driver stated that the cap was in good shape and not secured by the shipper after the CTMV was loaded.  The duration of the release occured no longer than 45 minutes.  The washout cap was found on the catwalk of the CTMV and installed.              Quality Event #66881.

column168: WEARING PROPER PPE WAS CALLED TO A SPILL AT THE HAZ-MAT DROP OFF AREA. A STAINED BOX WAS LEFT THERE BY A PACKAGE CAR DRIVER. THE DECISION TREE LED ME TO THE UKNOWN RESPONSE SHEET. THE BOX WAS PLACED INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY AND TAKEN BACK TO THE PSC AREA FOR FUTHER PROCESSING. AT THE PSC AREA THE BOX WAS OPENED TO FIND ONE GALLON OF TOLUENE THAT HAD LEAKED FROM A WHOLE THAT WAS IN THE TOP OF THE CAN COVERED BY DUCT TAPE. THERE WAS ALSO ANOTHER 1 GALLON CONTAINER THAT WAS A DOW CORNING CONFORMAL COATING WITH A FLAMMABLE LIQUID DIAMOND LABEL ON IT. SO I CALLED THE HELP DESK AND WAS TOLD TO HOLD ALL CONTENTS, TAKE PHOTO'S, AND ENTER THE TRACKING INTO ETT AS AN UNDECLAIRED HAZ-MAT. PACKAGE IS BEING HELD FOR INSPECTION.
column169: BOX SHOULD HAVE BEEN PROPERLY MARKED.

column168: RMP NOTICED PKG STARTED TO SMOKE. INSTRUCTED ALL PROCESSING TO BE STOPPED, PER CHAIN OF COMMAND. SPOKE WITH OUTSIDE RESPONDER - TAS AND WAS GIVEN ARRIVAL TIME OF 00:15. TAS ARRIVED AT 00:20 AND PROCESSED PKGS - CONTAINERIZED INTO 3 DMP PLASTIC BAGS AND PLACED INTO 55 GAL DRUM AND SEALED FOR DISPOSAL SHIPMENT. TAS FINISHED AND LEFT APPROX. 01:20. PKG HAD NO EXTERNAL LABELS, NO ORIENTATION ARROWS, NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR SHIPPING PAPERS. INSIDE PKG HAD NO PACKING OR PADDING. BOTTLES WERE LOOSE TO SLIDE AND BUMP AROUND WHICH CAUSED THE CAP OF ONE BOTTLE TO POP OFF.

LID WAS NOT TIGHT. I WAS ABLE TO HAND TIGHTEN IT A LITTLE. IT SOAKED A PORTION OF THE OUTER CARTON AND DID NOT LEAK ON ANY OTHER PACKAGES. I BROUGHT THE PACKAGE TO THE HAZMAT AREA AND PROCESSED IT AND CALLED THE UPS HAZMAT HOTLINE TO REPORT AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT.

column168: American Airlines Dangerous Goods Compliance HDQ was notified at approximately 11:30 CST on November 9, 2017 that Flight 90 had departed ORD for LHR and that a lithium battery shipment was on board that had not been notified to the Flight Crew.  It is American Airlines procedure that all lithium battery shipments will be notified to the Flight Crew via Notification To Captain or NOTOC.  Coordination was made between American Airlines Cargo in ORD, our Cargo Operations Center (COC) and Flight Dispatch to communicate via ACARS to the Crew what was on board the aircraft.  This was accomplished at approximately 11:39 CST on November 9, approximately two hours and 30 minutes into the flight from ORD to LHR.  The communication per ACARS was per below:     203: Event Date/Time = 09Nov17 17:39:35 (GMT) Device ID = FF99C3 Agent ID = FTW-C8C    Flt# = 0090 ORD LHR Dep Time (GMT) = 09Nov 15:10 Nose# = 8AV Reg# = N818AL Equip = 7878   History Type = QU  QU AIRCMAA  %.TULDDAA 091739 FROM   %DDLXCXA  % CMD  %AN N818AL/GL YKL  %- QUTULDDAA010090FTM  %                    %HI CAP..I WAS JUST NOTIFIED THAT YOU  %HAVE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS ONBOARD.  %THERE WAS NO NOTOC BUT I HAVE THE INFORMATION..  %LITHIUM BATTERY FOR MEDICAL DEVICE FROM DHL  %14.6 KILOS UN3091  %PACKING INSTRUCTION 970 SEC 2  %UNIT NUMBER AKE 70806AA  %DISP FISCHER  %PLZ ACK MSG NO. "3935$% END    The Crew Acknowledged receipt of the message per the request of the Dispatcher approximately 2 minutes later per the following:     204: Event Date/Time = 09Nov17 17:41:06 (GMT) Device ID = F30000 Agent ID = NO-AAA Employee # = 000000   Flt# = 0090 ORD LHR Dep Time (GMT) = 09Nov 15:10 Nose# = 8AV Reg# = N818AL Equip = 7878   History Type = PR  PR  QU TULDDAA  .DDLXCXA 091741  AGM  FI AA90/AN N818AL  DT DDL YYRV 091741 M19A  -  OS EGLL /FTM3935    American Airlines Flight 90 continued on uneventfully to LHR.
column169: Although there was an electronic record containing a reference to a lithium battery, the Air Waybill document did not have the required statement of "Lithium metal batteries in compliance with Section II of PI 970".  Therefore American Airlines Cargo personnel accepting the consolidated shipment of goods were unaware that the shipment contained any lithium batteries.  It was only after processing the shipment that a secondary pass discovered the reference in the electronic database, which set the reaction in motion to notify the Flight Crew.  Lithium batteries are a serious enough concern that it should be mandated for all shipments to have a formal shipper's declaration so that the air carrier is aware that consignments contain lithium batteries.

column168: The trailer was staged at our Charlotte operating center.  The next driver who went to pick it up found product in the crash box.  These trailers do not have gaskets, its just rubber lining meshing up to rubber lining on the dome lid.  They undid the dome lid and inspected.  The lining appeared to be fine.  After resecuring the dome and doing a pressure test it held fine.  The dried product was hardened to the trailer and had to be cleaned off at the tankwash.
column169: The driver who dropped it at Charlotte was brought in for training (securement and pre-trip / post-trip inspections) and had his bonus impacted as he had not reported it to the spill team and this should have been identified on the post-trip inspection.

column168: When removing the bottom outlet valve cap to install a hose for unloading at intended destination, approximately three cups of solvent was released to the concrete containment from the bottom outlet valve opening. There was a bucket under this connection, but a strong wind caused solvent to largely miss the bucket. Only the concrete containment pad was impacted; no soil or water were affected. Facility personnel donned the correct personal protective equipment and cleaned the impacted area with absorbents and spill pads. This waste material was disposed of in the appropriate branch waste stream. The tanker was offloaded without further incident. A later examination of the bottom valve in question determined that a rag had become partially stuck in the valve, preventing the valve from fully closing.    This release fell below the reporting requirements for the State of Ohio.
column169: There was no evidence of debris in the valve at the time this tank was loaded. The rag was likely introduced into this product stream inadvertently at one of the numerous collection points that collect this solvent. The driver was coached on better valve inspections before loading (to the extent that it is possible to inspect), and guidance will be passed on the the field to (wherever possible) strive to eliminate any foreign debris in this product stream.

ON TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 28, 2017, I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A PACKAGE ON PD-7 LVD. I RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT WITH MY PPE, DECISION TREE, AND SPILL CART. I SAW THAT THE PACKAGE WAS MARKED WITH A CORROSIVE DIAMOND LABEL AND HAZMAT SHIPPING PAPERS AND REFERRED TO MY DECISION TREE, WHICH LED ME TO THE CORROSIVE SOLIDS AND LIQUIDS RESPONSE SHEET. I DONNED MY PPE AND SILVER SHIELDS AND FOLLOWED THE RESPONSE ACTION STEPS. AFTER WHICH, I TOOK THE PACKAGE BACK TO PSC AND REFERRED TO THE WASTE DISPOSAL CHART AND DISPOSED OF THE CONTENTS ACCORDINGLY. AFTER WHICH, I DECONTAMINATED MY PPE.
column169: PACKAGING NEEDS BETTER/MORE PACKING TO HELP PREVENT SPILLAGE.

column168: Upon arrival at the Consignee, our driver noticed Hazardous Material on the CTMV and pavement.  Our driver investigated and found that he had not closed the CTMV air inlet valve at the top of the tank before departing the Shipper.  Our driver called for assistance and we sent a HazMat contractor to retrace the route.      Our reference no: 67137

1. When driver took off the dust cap on the external some product came out. This is not his fault. the external and internal valves were closed.   2. When he hooked up his hoses and began unloading a small spill came from the hoses where they were attached to the external. The gaskets were fine and not the issue. He had to put a shim on both sides and it worked then.  3. Before he put the shims on he needed to disconnect the hoses. In doing so he had another spill because he had to do a wet brake. This is his fault as he forgot to use his IM fitting on the external when hooking up his hoses. When he went to disconnect he didn’t have any way to bleed out the product and had to unhook while they were loaded. He took the blame for this and understands that he needed to use it.   4. In total maybe about 5 gallons spilled out between the 3 spills. The customer took care of the clean up per the driver.
column169: The driver was coached on proper unloading procedures. We also advised him to bring with him a special piece of equipment that allows him to bleed the lines when working with our Intermodal trailers.

On November 28, 2017, ESTES (#53 Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN1824, Sodium Hydroxide, 8, PG II, (PRO#0531747489) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel punctured (1) 330-gallon poly tote of product. Approximately 100-gallons of product has been released to the dock and parking lot. The caller indicated that the majority of the release is inside on the dock floor. Terminal personnel have placed down absorbent materials at this time.Contractor estimates that approximately 150 gallons of product has been lost. The parking lot has an impacted area of 30' x 80' and the dock floor has an impacted area of 20' x 20'. Contractor will utilize vinegar/water mixture to neutralize the area. Contractor indicated that approximately 100-gallons of product was released to the parking area and approximately 50-gallons to the dock floor. Contractor is using neutralizing and absorbent materials to clean the release at this time.The contractor reports the cleanup operations are going well on site. The team is currently transferring the remaining product from the damaged tote into a new, clean tote. However, the contractor has advised this product cannot be fully cleaned and neutralized with vinegar/water and absorbents. The impact to the parking lot is extensive. This area will need to be pressure washed to fully clean the parking lot. The team has advised a vacuum truck will be needed to collect the impacted waste water. Contractor reports they were advised that the asphalt parking was very recently paved. Therefore, pressure washing operations could damage the new asphalt. Therefore, the contractor is continuing to neutralize and clean the impacted area with absorbents. In order to fully clean and neutralize this product, additional time on site will be required. The team has generated (4) drums of absorbent waste at this time. Contractor has departed the site at this time and advised all waste has been containerized into 9-55 gallon poly open top drums and 1-275 gallon poly tote containing an estimated 120 gallons of product. Contractor has staged the waste on site pending disposal. A stain remains on the parking area due to the spilled product. Contractor has departed the site at this time.

column168: On 11/28/2017 at 0630 EST, a Dupre Logistics tractor-trailer was involved in a hazmat cargo incident on I-10-westbound at I-610 near Houston, TX. The driver of the Dupre tractor-trailer braked to avoid an accident causing the load in the trailer to shift forward. The trailer was hauling (10) - 330 gal poly IBC's and (3) 330 gallon poly totes containing UN1779 Formic Acid were shifted forward and went through the front of the trailer striking the cab. (1) of the totes fell over and made the entire trailer unstable. Approximately 1 gallon of Formic Acid released onto a small area of asphalt roadway from a leaking cap on one tote. There was no impact to any soils, drains or waterways. The driver of the tractor-trailer was transported to the hospital as a precaution but there was no exposure. All 7 lanes of I-10 WB were shut down from the hazmat release.   On November 28, 2017 at 1000 EST, the local fire department and Masters ARS (Hazmat contractors) arrived onsite for cleanup operations. They confirmed less than 1 gallon of UN1779 Formic Acid released onto a 6 ft x 1 ft area of concrete roadway from a leaking tote cap. (3) 330 gallon poly totes were shifted from the accident and needed to be transferred before the trailer was moved. All product from the damaged totes was transferred into (20) - 55 gallon poly drums for salvage product and placed on a relief trailer. The spilled material was neutralized with soda ash and solidified with absorbents for waste. All impacted areas were cleaned and no environmental impact remains.

column168: A vehicle operated by Safety Kleen Systems, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 2 gallons of material had  escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the container. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and  placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time of pick up, the drum was wrapped in plastic and secured with duct tape.  As the plastic was removed, the driver noted missing bungs and a small amount of duct tape around the top area of the drum.  The bungs were replaced and the drum loaded into the transport vehicle.  The drum was fine during transport and sat at the facility warehouse over the weekend.  As the drum was being offloaded for palletizing, it was noted approximately 2 gallons escaped from a small crack near the top of the drum.  It is determined that the remaining duct tape covered a small crack near the top seam of the drum.    Additional container management training will be conducted with all branch personnel to prevent this type of incident from recurring.  Should the driver come across any amount of duct tape on a drum, the drivers are instructed to over-pack at the customers site.

column14: INTERSECTION OF CR E AND CR 47
column168: DRIVER WAS HEADED WEST ON CR E PULLING A SET OF NH3 TANKS WHEN HE CRESTED THE HILL. THE COUNTY WAS GRADING THE GRAVEL ROAD AND THERE WAS A MOUND OF DIRT IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ROAD APPROXIMATELY 12 INCHES TAIL. WHEN THE DRIVER REALIZED HE WAS STRADDLING THE MOUND HE TRIED TO MOVE OVER AND THAT'S WHEN THE TANKS ROLLED OVER. WHEN THE TANKS ROLLED ONE OF THE VALVES CAME OPEN ABOUT ONE FULL TURN.
column169: IN THIS CIRCUMSTANCE THE EQUIPMENT DID PERFORM AS DESIGNED, THE FRAME PROTECTING THE VALVES WAS BENT BUT KEPT THE VALVES FROM SHEARING, ALTHOUGH THE OPEN DESIGN ALLOWED DIRT TO PLOW THROUGH OPENING THE HAND VALVE WHEEL THAT WAS THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE. THIS WAS IN A REMOTE AREA WHERE THE COUNTY ROAD CREW HAD NOT POSTED ANY WARNING SIGNS THAT THE ROAD WORK WAS TAKING PLACE. CORRECTIVE ACTIONS FOR OUR DRIVER IS TO TRAINING TO USE CAUTION WHEN MAKING ABRUPT MANEUVERS WHILE PULLING LOADED TRAILER AS THE SURGE OF THE PRODUCT WAS A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR, ALSO TOPPING THE HILL INTO THE SUN HE WAS NOT ABLE TO SEE THE GRADED MOUND IN THE ROADWAY.    COUNTY SHOULD POST ROADWORK SIGNS EVEN IN RURAL AREAS WHEN GRADING IS TAKING PLACE.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 AM ON 11/3/17 AND BEGAN UNLOADING. THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK FILLED UP AND FOR UNKNOWN REASONS THIS CAUSED THE HOSE LOCK-DOWN TO DISCONNECT. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR WAS ALSO ENGAGED AND WERE ALL ON SITE BY 9 AM ON 11/3/17. REMEDIATION WAS COMPLETED BY NOON ON 11/4/17 AND ALL ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES ADDRESSED TO SATISFACTION OF MDEQ.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: SUPERIOR PLUS ENERGY SERVICES (SPES) VEHICLE WAS PARKED ON THE SIDE OF ARMINGTON ROAD (A STRAIGHT AND RELATIVELY LEVEL ROADWAY), WITH ITS FLASHERS ENGAGED, MAKING A PROPANE DELIVERY, WHEN A PASSENGER CAR COLLIDED INTO THE REAR DRIVER'S SIDE OF THE PROPANE DELIVERY VEHICLE AT (WHAT IS BELIEVED TO BE) A HIGH RATE OF SPEED. THE ACCIDENT CAUSED A FIRE IN THE PASSENGER CAR'S ENGINE, AND COMPROMISED THE PIPING BETWEEN THE PROPANE CARGO TANK AND THE METER ON THE DELIVERY VEHICLE. THE PIPING WAS CRACKED, CAUSING THE PROPANE WITHIN TO VAPORIZE UPON CONTACT WITH THE OUTSIDE ATMOSPHERE, RESULTING IN A SUSTAINED STREAM OF PROPANE VAPOR EMITTING FROM THE PIPING.  THE SPES DRIVER RESCUED THE MOTORIST BY PULLING HER FROM HER BURNING CAR AND SUMMONED EMERGENCY SERVICES. THE RESPONDING FIRE DEPARTMENT EXTINGUISHED THE FLAMES, AND THE MOTORIST WAS FLOWN TO A HOSPITAL. SPES PERSONNEL AND VENDORS STEMMED THE FLOW OF PROPANE FROM THE DELIVERY VEHICLE BEFORE IT WAS TOWED TO A SPES FACILITY AND EMPTIED.
column169: NO CHANGES SUGGESTED. DUE TO THE NECESSITIES OF OPERATION AND THE IMPRACTICABILITY OF PARKING THE VEHICLE IN ANY OTHER PLACE, THE SPES VEHICLE WAS PARKED AT ITS LOCATION WITH ITS FLASHERS ILLUMINATED FOR A BRIEF PERIOD OF TIME IN ORDER TO DELIVER LP GAS TO A RESIDENTIAL CUSTOMER.

column168: THE SHIPMENT (AWB# 932 57980985) WAS TENDERED AS A CONSOLIDATED SHIPMENT. THERE IS NO MENTION OF ANY TYPE OF DANGEROUS GOODS ON THE AIRWAY BILL OF SUPPORTING DOCUMENTS.     THE SHIPMENT WAS ACCEPTED AND BUILT FOR THE FLIGHT.    ITEMS WERE NOT IN UN SPECIFICATION PACKAGING. JUST STRONG RIGID OUTER PACKAGING.    UPON ARRIVAL TO VS IN LHR, IT WAS NOTICED TWO BOXES HAD LABELS (SEE BELOW) ADVISING LITHIUM BATTERIES WERE IN THE BOX.     FREIGHT FORWARDER WAS CONTACTED CONCERNING THE ISSUE. THEY ADVISED THEY WERE NOT MADE AWARE OF ANY TYPE OF BATTERIES BEING ASSOCIATED TO THE SHIPMENT BY THE SHIPPER. THEY ADVISED THEY WOULD CONTACT THE SHIPPER FOR CONFIRMATION. THEY ADVISED LATER THAT THE SHIPMENT DID CONTAIN BATTERIES THAT WERE OKAY FOR AIR TRAVEL. THE LHR OFFICE IS IN THE PROCESS PREPARING DGD DOCUMENTS FOR THE SHIPMENT SO THAT IT MAY MOVE TO FINAL DESTINATION.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0630 THURSDAY MORNING NOV 30, 2017, MORRISON LOWERY WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON HWY 97 TOWARDS FMI BAGDAD HAULING A LOAD OF ACID FROM FMI MIAMI VIA BOL 2102855. AT APPROXIMATELY MILE MARKER 162 MR. LOWERY IN CTI UNIT 838 ATTEMPTED TO ROUND CORNER AND ENDED UP OVER TURNING TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT OFF OF SHOULDER OF ROAD. JAMES PALMER, TERRY WHITE AND MIKE RAZO WERE THE CTI EMPLOYEES ON LOCATION. DOME LID OF TRAILER 2' CAM LOCK VALVE WAS CRACKED CAUSING THE VERY SLOW RELEASE OF MATERIAL.
column169: CTI HAS ALREADY PUT OUT A PEOPLE-NET MESSAGE TO ALL DRIVERS. WE ARE GOING TO BE CONSTANTLY TALKING TO DRIVERS THAT ALL CTI TRUCKS TRAVELING ON HIGHWAY 97 ARE ONLY TO DO 35 MPH MAX. FAILURE TO COMPLY WILL CARRY SEVERE CONSEQUENCES AND PENALTIES. CTI TERMINAL MANAGERS AND SAFETY DEPARTMENTS WILL ACTIVELY PATROL HIGHWAY 97, SETTING UP SPEED TRAPS AND SPEED MONITORING BY FOLLOW CTI TRUCKS.     WE ARE WORKING WITH CUSTOMERS TO HAVE DOT EVALUATE THE ROADWAY FOR POSSIBLE ROAD CONSTRUCTION TO WIDEN ROAD.

column168: PER THE CHRISTIAN COUNTY SHERIFF REPORT (72113252): UNIT WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON PEMBROKE OAK GROVE RD. JUST NORTH OF 2675 PEMBROKE OAK GROVE RD., FOR AN UNKNOWN REASON, THE RIGHT FRONT WHEEL DROPPED OFF OF THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO STEER THE VEHICLE BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY BY TURNING LEFT. UNIT 1 WAS ABLE TO COME BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY BUT HAD BEEN OVER CORRECTED BY THE DRIVER. UNIT BEGAN TO SKID SIDEWAYS TO THE LEFT CAUSING THE FUEL IN THE TANKER TO SHIFT. THE WEIGHT OF THE FUEL THEN CAUSE THE TRAILER TO FLIP OVER ON THE RIGHT SIDE, BRING THE TRUCK WITH IT. THE TRUCK TRAILER FLIPPED ONTO THE RIGHT SIDE, SLID APPROXIMATELY 28 FEET, FLIPPED OVER AND SLID FOR ANOTHER APPROXIMATE 38 FEET WHERE IT CAME TO REST ON ITS ROOM. THE CONTENTS OF THE TANKER BEGAN SPILLING OUT ONTO THE ROADWAY. THE DRIVER WAS PULLED FROM THE WRECKAGE BY SOME FARMERS THAT WERE IN THE AREA. FIRST RESPONDERS ARRIVED ON SCENE AND SPOKE BRIEFLY TO THE DRIVER WHO STATED HE COULD NOT REMEMBER WHAT HAPPENED. THE DRIVER WAS COMPLAINING OF PAIN TO HIS HEAD, RIGHT LEG, AND CHEST. THE DRIVER WAS FLOWN FROM THE SCENE BY LIFE FLIGHT TO TRISTAR SKYLINE MEDICAL CENTER IN NASHVILLE, TN. CHRISTIAN COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT WAS CONTACTED IN REFERENCE TO THE FUEL SPILL WHO THEN CONTACTED THE ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY. JONE'S BROTHER TOWING WAS CONTACTED PER EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AS THEY ARE CERTIFIED FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TOWING. PER THE EPA REPRESENTATIVE, A SECOND TANKED WAS BROUGHT TO THE SCENE  TO OFFLOAD ALL REMAINING FUEL FROM UNIT. JONE'S BROTHERS TOWED UNIT 1, WAS IN CHARGE OF THE SECURE IT FOR AN INSPECTION BY KENTUCKY VEHICLE ENFORCEMENT. ECO ENERGY, THE OWNER OF UNIT 1, WAS IN CHARGE OF THE HAZMAT CLEANUP AND COORDINATED THE CLEANUP EFFORTS UNTIL THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS REMOVED. JUST BEFORE CLEARING THE SCENE I (SGT. MEACHAM) WAS INFORMED BY A REPRESENTATIVE OF ECO ENERGY THAT THE DRIVER HAD DIED FROM INJURIES.
column169: AFTER THE EVENT SEVERAL MEMBERS OF THE ECO ENERGY TEAM CONVENED TO DISCUSS PREVENTION MEASURES. ONE OF OUR HIGHEST PRIORITIES FOR PREVENTING FUTURE OCCURRENCES OF THIS NATURE IS TO CREATE AND DISTRIBUTE A LIST OF RESTRICTED ROADS WHICH WE DEEM UNSAFE FOR OUR DRIVERS. HIGHWAY 115 IS TWO-LANE, WITH CURVES AND SMALL DITCHES ON EITHER SIDE OF THE ROADS FOR SEVERAL INTERMITTENT STRETCHES. WE WILL POLL OUR DRIVERS NATIONWIDE ASKING FOR ROADS THEY SUGGEST WE RESTRICT, THEN CIRCULATE THE RESTRICTED ROADS LIST AND RECIRCULATE IT QUARTERLY. WE BELIEVE THIS PRACTICE OF POLLING FOR AND COMMUNICATING RESTRICTED ROADS BASED ON THE SPECIAL DIFFICULTIES THE POSE TO DRIVERS OPERATING TRANSPORT EQUIPMENT USED IN OUR LINE OF BUSINESS COULD BE DUPLICATED BEYOND ECO ENERGY. IN ADDITION TO A RESTRICTED ROADS INVENTORY, WE WILL PREPARE AN UPDATED TRAINING ON LOAD SHIFTING AND OVER-CORRECTION FOR DISSEMINATION QUARTER 1 OF 2018.

column168: A PCB CONTAINING TRANSFORMER WAS INADVERTENTLY SHIPPED TO JERRY ELECTRIC CO. IN COLMAN, SOUTH DAKOTA FOR RECYCLING AS A NON-PCB CONTAINING TRANSFORMER.     INITIAL ANALYSIS SHOWED THE TRANSFORMER HAD A PCB CONCENTRATION <50MG/KG.    THE TRANSFORMER CONTAINED TWO TANKS, THE SECOND TANK CONTAINED PCB'S AT A CONCENTRATION OVER 700,000MG/KG.    BASED OF THE INITIAL ANALYSIS JERRY'S ELECTRICAL CO. DRAINED THE TRANSFORMER OIL INTO THEIR 10,000 GALLON TANK, CONTAMINATING 9000 GALLONS OF OIL WITH PCB'S.    WEEKLY ANALYSIS OF THE USED OIL TANK SHOWED ELEVATED PCB LEVELS.     AN ANALYSIS OF THE PROCESSED TRANSFORMERS DETERMINED THAT A STANDARD TRANSFORMER CO. TRANSFORMER SERIAL NUMBER RAD0340 WAS THE SOURCE OF CONTAMINATION.    THERE WAS NO RELEASE TO THE ENVIRONMENT.    3. WSMR FIRST BECAME AWARE OF THE INCIDENT AND WAS NOTIFIED OF THE CHARACTERIZATION ISSUE ON 14 DEC 2017. THE HIGH PCB CONCENTRATION WAS CONFIRMED ON 10 JANUARY 2018

column14: ON EAST RIDGE ROAD NEAR AMES R
column168: ON MONDAY, NOVEMBER 13TH, 2017, 0730    DRIVER WAS DRIVING A DIST TRUCK NORTH ON EAST RIDGE ROAD IN CORNVILLE, ME. HE HAD ALREADY MADE ONE STOP FOR THE DAY.     TRAVELING NORTH AT 40 MPH, DRIVER WENT OVER SLIGHT RISE IN THE ROAD (NEAR AMES RD). AS WE WENT OVER THE SLIGHT RISE IN THE RD THE PASSENGER SIDE TIRES OF THE VEHICLE WENT OF THE PAVEMENT AND INTO THE SOFT SHOULDER.    THE VEHICLE WAS IN THE SOFT SHOULDER FOR 200 FT BEFORE THE VEHICLE STEERED BACK ONTO THE PAVEMENT. AS THE TRUCKS FRONT TIRES RETURNED TO THE PAVEMENT AND OVER A 4 INCH RISE - (EXPLAIN) THE TRUCK WENT HARD LEFT (TOWARDS DRIVER SIDE) THE DRIVER OVER CORRECTED STEERING RIGHT (PASSENGER SIDE) CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO ROLL ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE.    THE VEHICLE SLID ON THE PAVEMENT FOR 75 FT UNTIL IT HIT THE SOFT SHOULDER ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROAD CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO ROLLOVER. WHEN THE VEHICLE ROLLED THE TANK WAS PUNCTURED AND LEAKED OUT K1 AND #2 FUEL OIL. ESTIMATED LOSS WAS 1,400 GALLONS.
column169: DRIVER SHOULD HAVE BEEN AWARE OF THE SOFT SHOULDER AND THE DIP IN THE ROAD.

column168: The driver had successfully delivered product from 3 compartments of this 4 compartment cargo tank trailer. When removing the dust cap from compartment #4 he found the external valve and line between the internal and external valves was full of the transported product. 2 gallons of the paint material was released in the off loading area. Driver and plant personnel contained the material and cleaned the area.   The external valve was found to be inoperable. The dust cap was re-installed and the material returned to the shipper. The cargo tank trailer was cleaned and taken to a cargo tank repair facility. The seat on the external valve was found to be damaged. It appears the carter pin which secures the seat nut in place was missing and allowed the seat nut to back off allowing the seat to detach from the external valve stem thus making the device in-operable. The seat, nut and carter key were replaced, the seat surface was resurfaced to ensure a leak free closure. The internal valve was also serviced to ensure it had not been damaged and would be leak free.

column168: PROPANE BOBTAIL DELIVERY TRUCK DRIVING IN THE RIGHTMOST LANE DOING APPROXIMATELY 70 MPH. TRUCK WAS LOADED WITH APPROXIMATELY 2,000 GALLONS OF LIQUID PROPANE. THE TRUCK WAS REAR-ENDED BY ANOTHER VEHICLE, TRAVELING AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED CAUSING SUBSTANTIAL DAMAGE TO THE REAR OF THE BOBTAIL, THE IMPACT CRACKED AN EXTERNAL PIPE CAUSING A LEAK AND IMMEDIATE IGNITION OF THE PROPANE. THE LEAK WAS UNABLE TO BE STOPPED, SO IT WAS DETERMINED THAT WE LET THE REMAINING GAS BURN OFF. ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS BURNED OFF, NO LIQUID PROPANE WAS EVER SPILLED OR IN CONTACT WITH THE GROUND OR SURROUNDING AREAS. THE TANK WAS COOLED WITH WATER BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ONCE THE FIRE HAD BURNED OUT. THE DIESEL (MOTOR FUEL) TANKS WERE NOT DAMAGED, AND AS A RESULT, THERE WAS NEVER ANY LUCK OR SPILL FROM THEM.  ? #32 – WE HAVE RECEIVED NO RESPONSE COST BILL DUE TO THE FACT THAT WE WERE NOT AT FAULT IN THE ACCIDENT, THERE WAS NO CLEANUP COST DUE TO THERE NOT BEING A SPILL, ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS BURNED OFF.   ? # 34 THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE WAS HOSPITALIZED DUE TO THE IMPACT OF THE CRASH, HOWEVER, NOTHING TO DO WITH THE MATERIAL ON THE TRACK OR THE SUBSEQUENT FIRE.  OUR DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE ER, OBSERVED AND RELEASED, DUE TO THE IMPACT OF THE COLLISION ONLY.

column168: THE DRIVER OF THE CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE ARRIVED ON THE CUSTOMER’S PROPERY TO REFILL AN ABOVE-GROUND STORAGE TANK. AFTER PLACING THE NOZZLE TO FILL THE TANK WITH NUMBER 2 DIESEL, HE STEPPED AWAY FROM THE TANK TO SPEAK WITH THE CUSTOMER. THE DRIVER HEARD THE OVERFILL SHUT-OFF STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT BUT SAW FUEL FLOWING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK ONTO A GRAVEL AREA BESIDE THE AST.  THE DRIVER TOOK STEPS TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE AND CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR. THE GATEWAY FS, INC. SAFETY COORDINATOR WAS CONTACTED AT ABOUT 1100 HOURS AND ARRIVED ON-SCENE AT ABOUT 1230 HOURS. AFTER ASSESSING THE SITUATION, THE SAFETY COORDINATOR CONTACTED A LICENSED WASTE HAULER. THE WASTE HAULER ARRIVED ON-SCENE AT ABOUT 1400 HOURS AND CONTAMINATED GRAVEL AND SOIL WAS REMOVED WITH A SKID STEER WITH A BUCKET ATTACHMENT. THE WASTE WAS HAULED TO A LICENSED LANDFILL.   IN THIS CASE THE DRIVER RELIED ON THE OVERFILL SHUT-OFF TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT WHEN THE TANK WAS FULL. HOWEVER, THESE DEVICES OFTEN FAIL TO OPERATE IMMEDIATELY. HAD THE DRIVER BEEN WITHIN REACH OF THE NOZZLE IT IS REASONABLE THAT ANY RELEASE WOULD HAVE BEEN MINIMAL.

ON NOVEMBER 29, 2017, BRENNTAG MID-SOUTH PERSONNEL DISCOVERED A POTENTIAL GAS LEAK COMING FROM A BOX TRUCK BEING UTILIZED TO TRANSPORT  12-150 LBS CYLINDERS OF CHLORINE AND EIGHT (8) 150 LBS CYLINDERS OF SULFUR DIOXIDE. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED WHO THE ARRIVED ON SITE SHORTLY AFTER NOTIFICATION. TO MITIGATE THE EFFECTS OF THE RELEASE, AN AREA NO LESS THEN 300FT WAS CORDONED TO MOBILIZE TO THE SITE IN AN ATTEMPT TO MAKE A POSITIVE IDENTIFICATION OF THE MATERIAL BEING RELEASED. DUE TO THE GASES RAISING AN ALARM ON THE 5 GAS METER, THE CONTRACTOR WAS UNABLE TO MAKE ENTRY INTO THE BOX TRUCK TO PROPERLY CONDUCT AN INSPECTION, THE AREA REMAINED CORDONED OFF. CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES WAS NOTIFIED SHORTLY AFTER THE ABOVE EVENTS AND DISPATCHED A CREW FROM MARION ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. TO MOBILIZE TO THE SITE AND CONDUCT A PROPER INSPECTION OF THE BOX TRUCK. CREW MEMBERS DONNED LEVEL B PPE WITH SCBA AND MADE ENTRY INTO THE BOX TRUCK. IT WAS THEN THAT THE MATERIAL WAS IDENTIFIED AS SULFUR DIOXIDE AS WELL AS WHICH CYLINDER WAS DAMAGED (SEE ATTACHED PHOTOS). THE REMAINING CONTENTS IN THE CYLINDER WERE BLED OFF BY LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AND ATTENDANTS AT FACILITY INTO THE FACILITIES TREATMENT SYSTEM FOR COLLECTION. A SMALL HOLE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CYLINDER WAS DISCOVERED TO BE THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE. WITH THE BOX TRUCK OPENED, THE AREA WAS ALLOWED TO VENT OFF UNTIL NO ALARMS WERE RAISED UTILIZING A 5 GAS METER. THE DAMAGED CYCLINDER WAS WRAPPED IN POLLY SHEETING AND WAS LEFT WITH THE CARRIER FOR DISPOSAL. WITH THE AREA CONFIRMED TO BE SAFE AND NO FURTHER HAZARDS IDENTIFIED ON SITE, MARION ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. PERSONNEL DEMOBILIZED FROM THE SITE.
column169: CONDUCT PROPER INSPECTION AND TESTING OF ANY AND ALL CYLINDERS PRIOR TO FILLING WITH ANY MATERIAL. WHEN TRANSPORTING ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, UTILIZE THE PROPER PPE AND ENSURE PROPER OPERATION OF DETECTION METERS. HAVE ON HAND A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COMPLIANCE BOOD AS WELL AS AN UPDATED EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE AND TRAIN EMPLOYEES ON HOW TO PROPERLY UTILIZE.

column168: A 1” bleed valve started to leak HF during the unloading process.  The unloading process was stopped and line was cleared.  The trailer was returned to Geismar. Upon arrival at the site the valve was tested.  The valve was leaking at the stem packing.  The valve was found to have a 1-1/2” nut clip installed on the valve instead of a 1”.  This looseness can allow the hex nut to become loose reducing seal stem tightness.
column169: A precautionary retorque (both bonnet and stem) of all trailers with this type valve was immediately initiated before its next shipment.  A 30 day re-torque program has also been initiated. Incorrect nut clips will be replaced.  The clips are on expedited order.  In the meantime, each nut clip assembly will examined before shipment. If any nut clips are not installed correctly a double nut will be added to ensure seal stem tightness.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis
